dash;behavior interactions  Differences in food delivered to chicks by males and females of little auks (  Alle alle  ) on South Spitsbergen  When and why does my mother leave me? The question of brood desertion in the Dovekie (  Alle alle  )  Different tactics, one goal: Initial reproductive investments of males and females in a small Arctic seabird  Is the transition from biparental to male-only care in a monogamous seabird related to changes in body mass and stress level?  Extra-pair copulations are frequent but unsuccessful in a highly colonial seabird, the little auk,   Alle alle    Sex-specific parental care by incubating Little Auks (  Alle alle  )  No evidence of blood parasites in little auks (  Alle alle  ) breeding on Svalbard  Evolutionary endocrinology: The developing synthesis between endocrinology and evolutionary genetics  Evolutionarily stable reproductive strategies in sexual organisms: An integrated approach to life-history evolution and sex allocation  Growing evidence indicates that producing eggs may constitute a considerable cost of reproduction. If female parental care, which in many species exceeds male performance, is added to these initial costs, it may be concluded that females contribute more to reproduction than males. However, this additional burden on females should reduce their survival and skew the usually equal sex ratio, but this is generally not the case. A resolution of this apparent paradox requires studies estimating the parental investments of both sexes at different stages of breeding, with particular focus on the initial reproductive stage. In the present study, egg composition and its energetic value was estimated in the Dovekie (or Little Auk,   Alle alle  ), a seabird exhibiting bi-parental care except for the end of the chick-rearing period, when the female deserts the brood while the male continues the feeding and escorts the chick during fledging. Condition estimates (size-adjusted body mass and several hematological and biochemical parameters, including concentrations of hemoglobin, glucose, cholesterol, and triglycerides, as well as the leukocyte profile) were also examined in both sexes during the prelaying, laying/relaying, and chick-rearing periods. The egg composition and its energy content indicate that the energetic demands of egg production are not as high as previously assumed, and the non-resource&ndash;based costs in females seem to be similar to those experienced by males during the mating period (nest site and/or paternity guarding). However, it was also found that females had lower body mass than males throughout the whole breeding season, suggesting overall female-biased costs of reproduction despite very similar parental performance. This suggests that females are more susceptible to the negative effects of reproduction. If so, their earlier brood desertion may be a response to the additive costs of parental investments.  De plus en plus d'indices indiquent que la production des &oelig;ufs peut constituer un co&ucirc;t consid&eacute;rable de la reproduction. Si les soins parentaux prodigu&eacute;s par la femelle, lesquels surpassent la performance du m&acirc;le chez plusieurs esp&egrave;ces, sont ajout&eacute;s &agrave; ces co&ucirc;ts initiaux, on pourrait conclure que les femelles contribuent davantage &agrave; la reproduction que les m&acirc;les. Cependant, ce fardeau suppl&eacute;mentaire pour les femelles devrait r&eacute;duire leur survie et biaiser le rapport des sexes qui est habituellement &eacute;gal, mais ce n'est g&eacute;n&eacute;ralement pas le cas. La r&eacute;solution de ce paradoxe apparent requiert des &eacute;tudes qui estiment les investissements parentaux des deux sexes &agrave; diff&eacute;rents stades de la reproduction, avec une attention particuli&egrave;re sur le stade de reproduction initial. Dans la pr&eacute;sente &eacute;tude, la composition de l'&oelig;uf et sa valeur &eacute;nerg&eacute;tique ont &eacute;t&eacute; estim&eacute;es chez   Alle alle  , un oiseau marin pr&eacute;sentant des soins biparentaux sauf &agrave; la fin de la p&eacute;riode d'&eacute;levage du poussin, lorsque la femelle d&eacute;serte la nich&eacute;e alors que le m&acirc;le continue de nourrir et d'escorter le poussin pendant l'envol. Les estimations de la condition (masse corporelle ajust&eacute;e pour la taille et plusieurs param&egrave;tres h&eacute;matologiques et biochimiques, dont les concentrations en h&eacute;moglobine, en glucose, en cholest&eacute;rol et en triglyc&eacute;rides, ainsi que le profil des leukocytes) ont aussi &eacute;t&eacute; examin&eacute;es chez les deux sexes au cours des p&eacute;riodes de pr&eacute;-ponte, de ponte/relais et d'&eacute;levage du poussin. La composition de l'&oelig;uf et son contenu &eacute;nerg&eacute;tique indiquent que les demandes &eacute;nerg&eacute;tiques de la production de l'&oelig;uf ne sont pas aussi &eacute;lev&eacute;es que pr&eacute;vu et que les co&ucirc;ts non associ&eacute;s aux ressources chez les femelles semblent &ecirc;tre similaires &agrave; ceux des m&acirc;les au cours de la p&eacute;riode d'accouplement (d&eacute;fense du site de nidification ou de la paternit&eacute;). Toutefois, on a &eacute;galement trouv&eacute; que les femelles avaient une masse corporelle plus petite que les m&acirc;les tout au long de la saison de reproduction, sugg&eacute;rant des co&ucirc;ts de reproduction globaux biais&eacute;s en faveur des femelles malgr&eacute; une performance parentale similaire. Ceci sugg&egrave;re que les femelles sont plus sensibles aux effets n&eacute;gatifs de la reproduction. Si tel est le cas, leur d&eacute;sertion de la nich&eacute;e peut &ecirc;tre une r&eacute;ponse aux co&ucirc;ts additionnels des investissements parentaux.   Mots-cl&eacute;s:    Alle alle  , masse corporelle, cholest&eacute;rol, glucose, h&eacute;moglobine, rapport h&eacute;t&eacute;rophiles/lymphocytes, triglyc&eacute;rides  It has long been thought that the cost of avian reproduction is primarily related to chick rearing ( Lack 1947 ,  1968 ). However, more recent studies have suggested that producing eggs may also be an energetically expensive activity that requires additional nutrient acquisition and the mobilization of fat reserves ( Monaghan and Nager 1997 ,  Nilsson and Raberg 2001 ,  V&eacute;zina and Williams 2002 ,  Sanz-Anguilar et al. 2012 ). In several species, females that were made to lay additional eggs (through egg removal) had lower local return rates in the following year ( Nager and Monaghan 2000 ,  Visser and Lessells 2001 ). At present, the factors driving the costs of egg production are not clearly understood (reviewed in  Williams 2005 ), but empirical studies clearly indicate that this activity may constitute a burden that could affect the further reproductive performance of females.  If egg production is so costly, and given that in most bird species females provide at least half of the parental care (reviewed in  Cockburn 2006 ), one may conclude that females contribute to reproduction to a higher degree than males. However, such unequal contributions of the sexes would lead to differential survival of males and females and distortion of the usually equal operational sex ratio, which is, generally, not the case ( Cockburn et al. 2002 ). Moreover, unequal contributions of both sexes to reproduction contradict the theory of the evolutionary stable strategy of sexual reproduction ( Maynard-Smith 1982 ,  Zhang and Wang 1994 ). There are 2 possible explanations for this apparent paradox: (a) the cost of egg production is not as high as previously assumed or is compensated by the female during the egg formation process or at later stages of breeding; or (b) the initial costs of reproduction are similar for the 2 sexes, although expressed in a different way, i.e. egg production in females and nest site and/or paternity guarding in males.  A resolution of this paradox requires detailed studies that could estimate the parental investments of males and females at different stages of breeding, with particular attention paid to the initial reproductive stage. Although the parental investments of males and females have been the subject of many studies, these have usually focused on chick rearing (e.g.,  Golet et al. 2000 ,  Fyhn et al. 2001 ,  Golet et al. 2004 ), and occasionally on the incubation period (e.g.,  Visser and Lessells 2001 ,  de Heij et al. 2006 ). However, initial parental investments of the 2 sexes appear to be neglected in many studies on parental care (reviewed in  Sz&eacute;kely et al. 2000 ,  Alonzo 2010 ).  To gain insight into this issue, male and female body condition estimates were examined at the prelaying, laying/relaying, and chick-rearing stages in the Dovekie (or Little Auk,   Alle alle  ;  Figure 1 ). This is a small pelagic seabird, which breeds exclusively in the high Arctic ( Stempniewicz 2001 ). The Dovekie is socially and genetically monogamous ( Lifjeld et al. 2005 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2009a ), with negligible dimorphism (there are no differences in plumage appearance; males have a larger total head length than females but there is large overlap in measurements between the sexes;  Jakubas and Wojczulanis 2007 ). In this species, a female produces one egg annually. The cost of its production is unknown, but it is assumed to be high given the size of the egg (&sim;20&percnt; of the female body mass;  Stempniewicz 2001 ) and the fact that relaid eggs are usually smaller than the first one (by 2.7&percnt;;  Jakubas and Wojczulanis-Jakubas 2013 ). Male and female contributions to incubation and chick provisioning are similar ( Harding et al. 2004 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2009b ,  2012 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas and Jakubas 2012 ). Only at the end of the chick-rearing period (up to 4 days prior to fledging) does the female cease to feed the chick and depart the colony, while the male continues provisioning and escorts the fledgling during its first flight to the sea ( Stempniewicz 2001 ,  Harding et al. 2004 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas and Jakubas 2012 ). In fact, the earlier female brood desertion is a common trait of  Alcini  tribe including, apart from the Dovekie, Razorbill (  Alca torda  ), Thick-billed Murre (  Uria lomvia  ), and Common Murre (  U. aalge  ) ( Gaston and Jones 1998 ).  Adult Dovekies (  Alle alle  ). Photo credit: Katarzyna Wojczulanis-Jakubas  It has been proposed that this earlier female brood desertion in the Dovekie is related to her initial investments ( Harding et al. 2004 ). As a result of incurring the high costs related to the clutch production ( Erckmann 1983 ) and additional costs during the incubation and chick-rearing periods, a female would desert the brood when approaching a threshold of her own body reserves. However, studies examining male and female condition estimates during the incubation and chick-rearing period, including the late phase of breeding, did not provide support for the hypothesis of earlier female brood desertion due to poor body condition ( Jakubas et al. 2008 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2012 ). Without knowing the primary parental investments of both sexes, explaining the behavior of female Dovekies in consecutive phases of breeding is purely speculative.  The aim of this study was twofold. First, the crude composition, energetic value, and duration of yolk formation of the Dovekie egg were investigated to verify the assumption of high costs of egg production in the species. Second, condition estimates were compared between molecularly sexed males and females at the different stages of breeding: prelaying, laying, relaying (after removal of the first egg), and chick rearing to examine thoroughly the effect of primary parental investments on the birds' body condition.  The study was carried out in a large breeding colony of Dovekie on the Ariekammen slopes in Hornsund (SW Spitsbergen, Norway; 77&deg;00&prime;N, 15&deg;33&prime;E) in 2012. This area is considered one of the main breeding aggregations of the Dovekie on Svalbard ( Isaksen 1995 ).  To establish the costs that the Dovekie egg represents, eggs from the birds sampled for the examination of body condition estimates in the laying and relaying periods (see details below) were measured (length and breadth using calipers that are accurate to 0.1 mm). A total of 20 eggs were collected (within 24 hours after laying) from nests during the egg-removal treatment (see details below) and frozen at &minus;20&deg;C until laboratory analyses were performed (&sim;3 months). Additionally, unpublished data from eggs collected (within 24 hours of laying) from the same colony and analyzed in 1984 ( n  &equals; 21) and 1987 ( n  &equals; 14) by J. R. E. Taylor were also used in the present study.  To examine the effect of egg production on the female condition, individuals of both sexes were captured at 4 different stages of the breeding season: (a) during the prelaying period (14&ndash;15 days before the average time of egg laying obtained for the group of control nests); (b) 1&ndash;2 days after laying the egg; (c) 1&ndash;2 days after relaying, in the group of nests with egg removal; and (d) during the mid-chick rearing period (after 8&ndash;9 days of chick rearing, according to the median hatching time obtained for the group of control nests). The birds were captured in noose carpets spread in a specific colony area (&sim;200 m 2 ) during the prelaying (30 males and 21 females) and chick-rearing (14 males and 11 females) periods, or directly on the nests while incubating, 1&ndash;2 days after laying (21 breeding pairs) or 1&ndash;2 days after relaying (10 breeding pairs and 3 females). Following capture, birds were measured (head&ndash;bill length using a caliper with an accuracy of 0.1 mm), weighed (with a spring balance with an accuracy of 1 g), banded, and a small blood sample was collected (&sim;30&ndash;50 &mu;l according to a standard procedure;  Owen 2011 ) from the brachial vein. All birds were released without any harm after &sim;10 min of handling. The blood sample collected in a heparinized capillary was divided into subsamples in order to (a) analyze the concentration of hemoglobin (10 &mu;L) using a portable hemoglobin photometer (Hb 201&plus; System; HemoCue, &Aring;ngelholm, Sweden); (b) analyze the concentration of glucose, cholesterol, and triglycerides (5 &mu;L for each) using standard commercial strips and a portable photometer (CardioChek 1709; PTS, Indianapolis, Indiana, USA); (c) make an air-dried blood smear to examine the leukocyte profile (&sim;5 &mu;L); and (d) preserve material in 70&percnt; ethanol for further molecular sexing (the remaining blood sample was used for this purpose). In a small number of individuals, the amount of blood taken was not sufficient to perform the whole set of analyses; therefore, the sample size given varies across the studied body condition estimates. The values obtained for triglycerides and cholesterol concentrations were below the range specified by the CardioChek producer in 14&percnt; and 3&percnt; of samples, respectively. In such cases, the lowest measured value was assigned to the individual sampled.  To establish the date of egg laying, 380 potential nest burrows (mostly known to have contained a nest in the previous season) were inspected every day, starting from a week before the expected date of laying. Of the 380 control burrows, 264 turned out to be real nests, i.e. active later in the season. During each nest inspection, the adults found in the nests were banded to check the bird's identity in the egg laying phase. Nests with both partners banded were selected for adult blood sampling just after laying ( n  &equals; 21) and relaying ( n  &equals; 20). The rest of the nests with banded birds ( n  &equals; 79) were considered the control group from which the laying and hatching dates were calculated. To establish the hatching date, 32 nests from the control group were inspected every 2 days starting from a week before expected hatching, based on the assumption of a 28-day incubation period ( Stempniewicz 2001 ).  To induce the birds to relay, egg removal was performed in 20 nests. The treatment was performed very early in the season in order to increase the chance of relaying (see the results from an analogous treatment in  Jakubas and Wojczulanis-Jakubas 2013 ). Thus, the eggs were removed (and frozen for egg composition analysis, see details above) on the day of laying in the focal nests (first to fourth day of egg laying at the scale of the whole colony, when 25&percnt; of eggs had been laid in the 79 control nests). To minimize disturbance, the burrows with egg removal were rechecked for the first time 7 days after the treatment, and then every day until a replacement egg was found or until 29 days after the treatment in cases where the birds did not relay ( Jakubas and Wojczulanis-Jakubas 2013 ). The egg was relaid in 15 (75&percnt;) of nests, including 2 nests where birds were not recaptured.  Although the exact date of laying and hatching of each bird that was haphazardly captured in the colony during the prelaying and chick rearing periods was not known, the synchrony of egg laying and hatching in the control nests (79 eggs laid within 10 days and 32 hatched chicks within 5 days) allowed to assume a similar timing of breeding for all individuals (14&ndash;15 days prior to egg laying and 8&ndash;9 days of chick rearing, according to the median date of laying and hatching in the control nests, respectively).  The following estimates describing condition were used: body mass corrected for body size, concentration of hemoglobin (g L &minus;1 ), glucose (mg dL &minus;1 ), cholesterol (mg dL &minus;1 ), and triglycerides (mg dL &minus;1 ), heterophil-to-lymphocyte ratio, and the percentages of the 2 leukocyte types. Calculation of the size-adjusted body mass provides the cleanest way to separate the effects of condition from the effects of body size ( Reist 1985 ,  Jakob et al. 1996 ). It has been shown in many bird species including the Dovekie that body mass (appropriately corrected for body size) decreases under conditions of food deprivation and in response to elevated efforts related to parental performance (e.g.,  Taylor 1994 ,  Moe et al. 2002 ,  Williams et al. 2007 ). Multiple methods of correction of body mass for body size have been proposed. Of those, scaled mass index (SMI) recently proposed by  Peig and Green (2009)  seems to be the most efficient in the correction ( Peig and Green 2010 ). The SMI standardizes all individuals to the same body size, adjusting their body mass to the one they would have at their new body size in accordance with the scaling trend between body mass and body size ( Peig and Green 2009 ,  2010 ). Hemoglobin concentration is a measure of the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood ( Cambell 1995 ); it may serve as an approximate parameter of metabolic potential ( Kostelecka-Myrcha 1997 ,  Ba&nacute;bura et al. 2007 ,  Minias et al. 2013 ). There is some evidence that blood of more active species of birds has a higher hemoglobin content than that of less active species (e.g.,  Palomeque et al. 1980 ,  Viscor et al. 1984 ). Glucose levels are expected to be higher in chronically stressed birds, as such individuals should have a greater ability to mobilize energy for immediate muscle use at the expense of maintenance or reproduction ( Butler and Bishop 2000 ,  Clinchy et al. 2004 ). In contrast, the triglycerides level is expected to be lower in chronically stressed individuals ( Remage-Healey and Romero 2001 ). The concentration of cholesterol has been suggested to reliably indicate periods of food deprivation, as it decreases with diminution of body mass ( Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2002 ). The leukocyte profiles provide a convenient measure of integrated immune function ( Davis 2005 ,  Salvante 2006 ,  Davis et al. 2008 ), with lymphocytes and heterophils being responsible for pathogen-specific and non-specific immune responses, respectively ( Fudge 1989 ,  Campbell 1995 ); as a result, both increase during immunological challenges ( Eeva et al. 2005 ). The heterophil-to-lymphocyte ratio (H/L) is known to increase along with efforts associated with reproduction (mostly through a decrease in the number of lymphocytes), when birds facing the problem of limited energy resources reach a trade-off by partially suppressing their immune system ( Salvante 2006 ,  Davis et al. 2008 ).  Crude egg composition, energetic values, and the duration of yolk formation were analyzed using 3 sets of eggs. Based on the first set, which was composed of eggs collected in 2012 ( n  &equals; 19), crude egg composition and energetic values were established. The eggs were thawed and carefully divided into shell and the remaining content (yolk and albumen). Both components were weighed separately to an accuracy of 0.01 g (wet weight), then dried at 60&deg;C to constant mass and weighed again (dry weight) with the same level of accuracy. The energetic value of the homogenized egg content was measured using the C 7000 calorimetric system (IKA-Werke, Staufen, Germany). Two samples of dried egg content were examined and values were averaged (mean error &equals; 1.01&percnt;,  n  &equals; 19) for each egg. The energetic value was expressed as kJ g &minus;1  and calculated for the whole egg.  More detailed analysis of egg composition was performed in 1984 based on the second set of eggs which was collected in that season ( n  &equals; 21). The eggs were weighed just after collection (wet weight) and then carefully divided into shell, albumen, and yolk and weighed separately (0.1 g accuracy). All components were dried (at 60&deg;C to constant mass) and weighed separately again (dry weight). Lipids were extracted from the yolk in the Soxhlet apparatus with petroleum ether. This solvent efficiently eluted lipids, as the additional extraction of 4 yolks in acetone increased the mass of extracted lipids by only 2.8&percnt;.  Finally, based on eggs collected and analyzed in 1987 ( n  &equals; 14, taken from the nests within 24 hr after laying), the duration of the period of rapid yolk deposition was determined as described by  Grau (1976) . The eggs were frozen just after collection at &minus;20&deg;C overnight. Shells were removed and the frozen contents were fixed in 4&percnt; formalin at 65&deg;C for 16 hr. The yolks, after being freed from the albumen, were cut in half, and one half was immersed in 6&percnt; potassium dichromate for 16 hr at 65&deg;C. Rings of pale- and dark-staining yolk were counted. A pair of one light and one dark ring marked each 24-hr period of yolk deposition.  The blood smears were stained using the May&ndash;Gr&uuml;newald&ndash;Giemsa method ( Lillie 1977 ) with an Aerospray Hematology cytocentrifuge (Wescor, Logan, Utah, USA). Blood cells were examined by 400&ndash;1000&ndash;fold microscopy. The proportion of different types of leukocytes (lymphocytes, heterophils, monocytes, eosinophils, and basophils) was assessed based on the examination of 100 leukocytes under oil immersion. Due to the low numbers of monocytes, eosinophils, and basophils, these leukocytes were not considered in further analyses.  Sexing was performed utilizing DNA extracted from blood (A&amp;A Biotechnology, Gdynia, Poland). The primers P2 and P8 were used according to the protocol described by  Griffiths et al. (1998) , using a 50&deg;C annealing temperature for the PCR reaction. These primers amplify a 390-bp fragment on the W chromosome (in females only) and a 370-bp fragment on the Z chromosome (in both sexes) ( Griffiths et al. 1998 ). This size difference was clearly visible under UV light when the fragments were separated for 2 hr at 55 V on a 3&percnt; agarose gel containing ethidium bromide.  The assumptions of normality and homogeneity of variance were checked for all variables using the Shapiro&ndash;Wilk and Levene's tests, respectively. All variables met assumptions of parametric analyses, except for triglycerides concentrations and the percentage of heterophils and lymphocytes. Those 2 variables were arcsine square-root transformed to meet the assumptions of the parametric analyses ( Zar 1999 ). A  P  value of 0.05 was considered the threshold for significant differences, except for multiple comparisons, when the levels of alpha were decreased for significance following Benjamini&ndash;Yekutieli correction (2001). The analyses were performed in SPSS 21 (IBM, Armonk, New York, USA) and STATISTICA 9.1 (StatSoft, Tulsa, Oklahoma, USA).  Separate general linear mixed model (GLMM) analyses were performed for each of the body condition estimates: body-scaled mass, concentrations of hemoglobin, glucose, cholesterol, and triglycerides, and relative number of heterophils and lymphocytes and the H/L ratio (dependent variables), with breeding phase and the sex of birds included as the fixed factors. As pair members were sampled during the laying and relaying period, nest identity was included in the models as the random factor. In all models, the interaction between the breeding phase and the sex of birds was included. Sums of squares of type III were used in all analyses. The Newman&ndash;Keuls test was used as post-hoc for the GLMM analyses.  Based on the egg measurements, egg volume (length &times; breadth 2 ) and egg shape index (length-to-breadth ratio) were calculated for the first and second eggs. The values were presented as mean &plusmn; SD. Both variables for the first and relaid eggs from the same females were investigated using Student's  t -test for dependent variables and Pearson correlation. The volume and shape of the first eggs were analyzed with each of the condition estimates of the focal females using the Pearson correlation. The relationship between the total volume of the 2 eggs and the condition estimates of relaying females was analyzed using the Pearson correlation coefficient.  Eggshells constituted 10&ndash;14&percnt; (1984&ndash;2012) and 25&ndash;27&percnt; (1984&ndash;2012) of the total wet and dry weight, respectively. Significant interannual differences were found for both wet and dry weight of the eggshell but not for the wet and dry weight of the egg content (yolk &plus; albumen) or the total weight ( Table 1 ).  Basic characteristics (mean &plusmn; SD) of Dovekie eggs collected in 1984 and 2012.  The yolk, with a wet weight of 9.80 &plusmn; 0.71 g ( n  &equals; 21) and a dry weight of 5.08 &plusmn; 0.41 g ( n  &equals; 21), constituted 31&percnt; of the total wet and 52&percnt; of the dry weight of the egg on average. The yolk consisted of lipids equal to 55&percnt; of the yolk dry weight (2.78 &plusmn; 0.22 g,  n  &equals; 19). The albumen, with a wet weight of 17.79 &plusmn; 1.67 g ( n  &equals; 21) and a dry weight of 2.29 &plusmn; 0.39 g ( n  &equals; 21), made up an average of 56&percnt; and 23&percnt; of the total wet and dry weight of the egg, respectively.  The energetic value of the average egg was 198.28 &plusmn; 20.20 kJ ( n  &equals; 20; 28.64 &plusmn; 0.55 kJ g &minus;1  of the dry weight). The yolk was formed during an average period of 5.3 &plusmn; 0.8 days (range: 4&ndash;6,  n  &equals; 14). The yolk-to-albumen ratio was on average 0.6:1 for wet weight and 2.3:1 for dry weight.  Body-scaled mass was not found to be significantly influenced by the phase of breeding but by the sex of birds (GLMM;  Table 2  and  Figure 2 ), with females being lighter than males ( Figure 2 ). There was no significant interaction between sex and phase of breeding ( Table 2 ).  The effects of sex and phase of breeding on the body-scaled mass, concentration of hemoglobin, glucose, triglycerides, and cholesterol in the Dovekie (GLMM, ANOVA). The asterisk indicates arcsine square-root&ndash;transformed variable.  Body-scaled mass: body mass corrected for body size (boxes are means and SD; whiskers 