etic expenses associated with the process of egg formation.  Owing to the food preferences of the Dovekie for energy-rich Arctic copepods, consisting of 36.8&percnt; lipids in dry mass ( Taylor and Konarzewski 1992 ) and occurring in great abundance in cold water masses in the vicinity of the breeding colonies (e.g.,  Kwasniewski et al. 2012 ), the female may quite easily collect sufficient energy resources to form the egg. Assuming 75&percnt; efficiency in the transformation of the consumed energy to the egg ( Carey 1996 ), Dovekie females need 219 kJ per yolk, which is the most costly part of the egg. Given the time required for yolk formation (5.3 days, reported in this study), each female needs 41.3 kJ day &minus;1  to form the yolk. This corresponds to 6.1 g of food (mean caloric value of the Dovekie food is 6.75 kJ g &minus;1 ;  Taylor and Konarzewski 1992 ), in other words, up to 2 average food loads brought by the females to the chick (3.5 g, with a range of 1.6&ndash;6.9;  Wojczulanis et al. 2006 ). Providing this level of energy resources does not seem to be a significant burden.  Egg-producing Dovekie females could rely on exogenous resources, thus employing the &ldquo;income&rdquo; breeding strategy ( sensu   J&ouml;nsson 1997 ). This would be in agreement with the observation that the females hardly visited the colony for 5 days prior to laying ( Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2014 ). Being outside the colony, females are likely to forage extensively for the purpose of fueling the egg-formation process. It is worth stressing that the time of the female &ldquo;exodus&rdquo; corresponds fairly well with the 5.3 days required for yolk formation that was revealed in the present study. Indeed, Dovekie females seem to be quite efficient in producing their egg, as the time required for yolk formation seems to be very short. Females of the Cassin's Auklet (  Ptychoramphus aleuticus  ) produce an egg similar in size to that of Dovekies, but need 3 days longer to produce the yolk ( Astheimer 1986 ). Duration of yolk formation in the Dovekie is shorter than in any of the 40 seabird species listed by  Astheimer and Grau (1990) , including 5 species that lay smaller eggs.  From a purely energetic point of view, given the energy content of the egg, its production constitutes 23&percnt; of the resting metabolism rate of adult Dovekie (RMR, estimated on 178 kJ day &minus;1 ;  Gabrielsen et al. 1991 ), while a 4-fold RMR increase is characteristic for chick-rearing adults ( Gabrielsen et al. 1991 ). Indeed, hemoglobin concentration was significantly lower during the laying and relaying periods than in the prelaying and chick-rearing periods. Given that hemoglobin level was expected to correlate with the maximum oxygen-transport rate and the potential metabolic rate ( Kostelecka-Myrcha 1997 ), the pattern of changes in that parameter suggests that egg production is not as energy consuming as activities performed during the prelaying and chick-rearing periods. Also, glucose concentrations varied throughout the breeding period, with lower levels reported during the egg-laying period compared with the prelaying and chick-rearing periods. This suggests relatively low stress levels of birds during the egg-laying period. Finally, neither triglycerides nor cholesterol indicated the females' poorer nutritional state during the egg-laying period compared with the other phases of breeding.  Nevertheless, body-scaled mass of females was significantly lower compared with males, although that was apparent for all examined breeding phases, i.e. not specific to the egg-laying period. That implies 2 issues. First, the cost of egg laying in terms of body mass loss are comparable to the costs of performing parental activities during chick rearing. Second, obtaining food for self-maintenance during both the egg-laying and chick-rearing periods was not so straightforward as it supposed to be (see above), at least for the females. Although males and females seem to provide parental care (incubation, chick brooding, and feeding) at very similar levels ( Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2009b ,  2012 ), the cost may be different for the 2 sexes. It has been shown for other species, for instance in the Black-legged Kittiwake (  Rissa tridactyla  ), that the same parental activity represents different costs for males and females ( Fyhn et al. 2001 ), and that may be manifested in differentiated body condition ( Moe et al. 2002 ). Moreover, it is possible that sex differences in Dovekie body mass might have been season-specific, as some other studies comparing body mass between males and females during particular phases of breeding did not show similar sex differences ( Jakubas et al. 2008 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2012 ,  2014 ). Thus, in some years the costs of all parental activities may be comparable between the sexes, but in less favorable circumstances, females may pay higher prices.  Some nutrients crucial to egg formation may be difficult to obtain for Dovekie females regardless of the season, constituting a constraint in egg production.  Jacobs et al. (2009)  found that certain fatty acids were depleted in the eggs relaid by Thick-billed Murre females while they were foraging on the local food resources. Also calcium, which is crucial for eggshell formation ( Taylor 1970 ), may limit egg production, as the food consumed by Dovekies contains very little of that element ( Taylor and Konarzewski 1992 ). There are some facts that seem to support this: (a) the relaid eggs were smaller than the initial ones ( Jakubas and Wojczulanis-Jakubas 2013 , this study), suggesting calcium limitation; (b) inter-seasonal differences in the mass of eggshells might be the result of interannual differences in calcium availability; and (c) the mass of the sternum in Dovekie females decreases by 9&percnt; after egg laying (J.R.E. Taylor, personal observation).  There are also other factors that may constitute a cost of egg formation, and their effect can occur over months or even years. There are non-resource&ndash;based costs that are associated with multiple physiological effects of reproductive hormones (reviewed in  Williams 2005 ). In such context, the lower level of hemoglobin concentration during the egg-laying period might be explained by hemodilution associated with osmoregulatory adjustments to elevated levels of lipoprotein yolk precursors ( Kern et al. 1972 ). Such an explanation was presented for some passerines, in which a decrease of red blood cell count was recorded at egg laying ( Kern et al. 1972 ,  Williams et al. 2004 ,  Wagner et al. 2008 ). Also, a decrease in the hemoglobin concentration might be due to a direct hormone-dependent (estradiol) inhibition of red blood cell production ( Kern et al. 1972 ,  Williams et al. 2004 ).  Another variable that could be explained in the light of non-resource&ndash;based costs of egg production is the number of lymphocytes that decreased significantly at the time of laying and prelaying, with a simultaneous increase in heterophils and an adequate elevation of the H/L ratio. The changes were consistent with the potential mechanisms of reallocation of resources from the immune system to egg production ( Gustafsson et al. 1994 ). It has been found in several species that egg-laying females (especially those which are forced to produce a larger than usual number of eggs) appeared to have a higher susceptibility to parasite infection due to the changes in the leukocyte profiles (e.g.,  Gustafsson et al. 1994 ,  Oppliger et al. 1996 ). Since all of these studies were conducted in parasite-abundant environments, there was a problem with discerning the cause and effect (i.e. whether the egg production effort caused changes in the immunocompetence and resulted in a higher parasite load, or infected individuals were in poorer condition and therefore likely to lay smaller clutches). The situation is much clearer in the Dovekie, for which there is no evidence of hemoparasite infection, possibly due to the lack of parasite vectors in the polar environment ( Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2010 ). Thus, the changes in the leukocyte profiles in females were likely to be related to the process of egg formation.  The cost of egg laying may also vary in different females, depending on their age and/or quality. The present results showed females that had laid a first egg of low-energy content had elevated stress levels after relaying, expressed in low triglyceride concentration and elevated H/L ratio. This suggests that egg formation is costly for females laying low-energy&ndash;content eggs, possibly young and/or low-quality individuals. On the other hand, it seems that for females producing high-energy&ndash;content first eggs, extra production of the replacement egg does not result in elevated stress level.  Interestingly, males experienced pronounced changes in hemoglobin and glucose concentrations as well as in the leukocyte profile throughout the breeding season, with a very similar pattern to that reported for females. The similarity of changes in male and female leukocyte profiles and hemoglobin concentrations during the prelaying and laying/relaying periods suggests that the changes have a hormonal basis. Both egg and sperm production are related to the great changes in hormone secretion in both sexes ( Kern et al. 1972 ,  Ketterson and Nolan 1999 ,  Wingfield et al. 2001 ,  Williams 2005 ). The steroid hormones and gonadotropins increase rapidly to a peak during courtship, territory defense, and egg laying ( Williams 1999 ,  Wingfield et al. 2001 ). Many, if not all, hormones involved in reproduction have widespread (pleiotropic) effects on a wide range of physiological systems ( Finch and Rose 1995 ,  Ketterson and Nolan 1999 ,  Williams et al. 2005 ,  Zera et al. 2007 ). Therefore, the 2 sexes, although being under the influence of different hormones, may experience their broad pleiotropic effect, incurring non-resource&ndash;based costs of reproduction ( Ketterson and Nolan 1999 ). Hence, all changes in biochemistry and hematological parameters explained by egg production in females might be interpreted in the context of specific activity, such as mate and territory defense in males.  Dovekie females cease chick feeding and depart the colony a few days (up to 4) before chick fledging, while males continue to provide food for the young ( Harding et al. 2004 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas and Jakubas 2012 ). It has been hypothesized that the females desert the brood earlier than males due to the high costs of egg formation ( Harding et al. 2004 ); however, the results of other studies have questioned this hypothesis ( Jakubas et al. 2008 ,  Wojczulanis-Jakubas et al. 2009b ,  2012 ). The present study shows that that egg production in the Dovekie is not so energetically demanding as it was previously assumed, and most of the necessary nutrients may be obtained from exogenous resources. Also, the non-resource&ndash;based costs of egg production seem to be similar to those that the males experience during the mating period due to male-specific activities (nest site and mate defense) and hormonal changes. In that context, it seems that costs of egg production per se are not the only reason for female brood abandonment. However, the present study also showed that Dovekie females had lower body mass compared with males throughout the whole breeding season, suggesting female-biased costs of reproduction, at least in the studied season. It indicates, therefore, that females are more prone to the lowering of body condition than males. If so, they may be predisposed for brood desertion more than males due to the additive effect of all parental investments, including egg production.  Summing up, the results of the present study strongly suggest that the common assumption of the high cost of egg production incurred by avian females is more complex and should be verified. It seems that when resources are not limited during the egg-laying period, the energetic costs of egg production may be negligible, and then non-resource costs only may affect the female's body condition. Therefore, resource and non-resource costs of egg production should be examined separately in future studies. Also, showing similarity of the sexes in the non-resource&ndash;based costs of the mating period, the present study suggests that the males' initial performance, typically neglected, should be seriously considered in future studies of avian parental investments.  Thanks go to Marek Konarzewski (1984 and 1987 seasons) and Mateusz Barcikowski (2013 season) for participation in the fieldwork, as well as to Proof-Reading Service (UK) for improvements in English usage. The study was supported financially by grants from the University of Gda&nacute;sk (538-L120-0814-12 to KWJ) and DEC-2011/01/N/NZ8/04569 to DK. All fieldwork was performed under permission of the Norwegian Animal Research Authority and the Governor of Svalbard. 